                            <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
                                Cleaning the bathroom can often feel like a daunting task, especially when you want to ensure every corner is spotless. However, with the right strategy and a solid routine, cleaning your bathroom from top to bottom can be easy and efficient. A clean bathroom not only improves the overall appearance of your home but also promotes hygiene and comfort for everyone who uses it.
                            </p>
    
                            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Start with Dusting the Ceiling and Light Fixtures</h2>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">The first step in cleaning your bathroom is to tackle the ceiling and light fixtures. Starting at the top ensures that falling dust doesn't ruin surfaces you've already cleaned.</p>
                            <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-700 space-y-2 mb-6">
                                <li><strong>Dust the ceiling:</strong> Use a long-handled duster to reach corners and remove cobwebs.</li>
                                <li><strong>Clean light fixtures:</strong> Wipe down fixtures with a damp cloth (ensure lights are off).</li>
                                <li><strong>Check ventilation fans:</strong> Vacuum out dust from vent covers to maintain proper airflow.</li>
                            </ul>
    
                            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Clean Mirrors and Glass Surfaces</h2>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Mirrors and glass surfaces can accumulate water spots and soap scum. Brighten the room by making these surfaces shine.</p>
                            <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-700 space-y-2 mb-6">
                                <li><strong>Use a glass cleaner:</strong> Spray vinegar and water or a commercial cleaner and wipe with a microfiber cloth.</li>
                                <li><strong>Clean glass shower doors:</strong> Use a non-abrasive cleaner to remove hard water stains.</li>
                                <li><strong>Shine the faucets:</strong> Wipe down metal handles to remove spots.</li>
                            </ul>
    
                            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Scrub the Sink and Countertop</h2>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Clear away toiletries to ensure you reach every inch of the countertop and sink basin.</p>
                            <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-700 space-y-2 mb-6">
                                <li><strong>Clear the area:</strong> Remove all items from the counter first.</li>
                                <li><strong>Scrub the sink:</strong> Use a mild all-purpose cleaner for the basin and drain.</li>
                                <li><strong>Disinfect:</strong> Wipe the entire surface with a disinfectant to kill germs.</li>
                            </ul>
    
                            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Tackle the Toilet Bowl and Surrounding Areas</h2>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">The toilet requires specific attention to maintain hygiene and prevent odors.</p>
                            <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-700 space-y-2 mb-6">
                                <li><strong>Inside the bowl:</strong> Use a toilet brush and specialized cleaner, reaching under the rim.</li>
                                <li><strong>Exterior wipe-down:</strong> Clean the tank, handle, lid, and base with disinfectant.</li>
                                <li><strong>Floor area:</strong> Ensure the floor around the toilet base is thoroughly mopped.</li>
                            </ul>
    
                            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Focus on the Shower and Tub</h2>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">This area is prone to mold and mildew. Regular scrubbing keeps it a safe, clean space for bathing.</p>
                            
                            <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-700 space-y-2 mb-6">
                                <li><strong>Scrub tiles and grout:</strong> Use baking soda and water to lift stains from grout lines.</li>
                                <li><strong>Clean the showerhead:</strong> Soak in vinegar to remove mineral buildup.</li>
                                <li><strong>Wipe shower walls:</strong> Use a squeegee or cloth to prevent mold accumulation.</li>
                            </ul>
    
                            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Clean and Disinfect Bathroom Floors</h2>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Finish the cleaning process by focusing on the floor, where dust and hair accumulate.</p>
                            <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-700 space-y-2 mb-6">
                                <li><strong>Sweep or vacuum:</strong> Clear debris before getting the floor wet.</li>
                                <li><strong>Mop thoroughly:</strong> Use a cleaner suitable for your floor type (tile, vinyl, etc.).</li>
                                <li><strong>Disinfect high-traffic spots:</strong> Focus on the areas directly in front of the sink and toilet.</li>
                            </ul>
    
                            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Maintenance and Consistency</h2>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Don't forget your linens! Wash towels and bath mats weekly. To keep your results lasting, clean your tools (like the toilet brush and cloths) after every use and stick to a weekly schedule to prevent grime build-up.</p>
    
                            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6">FAQs</h2>
